<subSubSection id="5E61BDAC8B9EC7B6CAB93054DF7B0C02" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="AADAECCF3386479BF87D303EE094BBA7" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName id="DE6C2A48CEF2B40936D2D4612FFAB559" authorityName="Say" authorityYear="1823" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidium" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidium levigatum" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="levigatum">Bembidium levigatum</taxonomicName>
Say, 1823: 84. Lectotype female in MNHN, designated by 
<bibRefCitation id="BD6CC1DDE29909F57A6C23E426E5568F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1155/1969/90590" author="Lindroth, CH" journalOrPublisher="Psyche" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="326 - 361" refId="B24" refString="Lindroth, CH, Freitag, R, 1969. North American ground-beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, excluding Cicindelinae) described by Thomas Say: designation of lectotypes and neotypes. Psyche 76: 326 - 361, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1155/1969/90590" title="North American ground-beetles (Coleoptera, Carabidae, excluding Cicindelinae) described by Thomas Say: designation of lectotypes and neotypes." url="https://doi.org/10.1155/1969/90590" volume="76" year="1969">Lindroth and Freitag (1969)</bibRefCitation>
. Type locality Missouri.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="EEE55F1B900F1BF2A935AC0070710683" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
<taxonomicName id="2AA3AF0B945F96F00CBBF3D54AA11863" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidion laevigatum subsp. delawarense" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="laevigatum" subSpecies="delawarense">Bembidion laevigatum delawarense</taxonomicName>
Casey, 1924: 24. Holotype male in USNM (type number 36814), examined. Type locality Pennsylvania.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="592F1370D1FD79DE86D682EA36A384AD" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="D7115F94EA1196C88E4298D4226A6043" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Diagnosis and geographic distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AD8EB3A7522C88DEFA21DCFEDE550A4E" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">
Adults of this species are large and distinctively wide, with a broad, rounded prothorax (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="D93A4C85217B56920ACC0C3B5A8791F9" captionStart="Figure 8" captionStartId="F8" captionText="Figure 8. Adult males of subgenus Bembidion Hydrium A Bembidion levigatum (voucher V 100820, from USA: Utah: Grand Co., Moab, Colorado River, 1190 m, 38.5739 ° N, 109.5769 ° W) and B B. mimbres (a paratype from the type locality, voucher V 101458). Scale bars: 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1007.60012.figure8" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/492372" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">8A</figureCitation>
), and with a very shiny dorsal surface, with a green or bluish metallic reflection. The clypeus, frons, anterior corner of the prothorax, and all elytral intervals have long setae in addition to the standard set in 
<taxonomicName id="0FA29671D16A8E27B8EA4C262BF5C740" authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bembidion" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="83C3123EAAFD9E8B3ACE309FB07C694B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">Bembidion</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the prosternum has four or more setae. Aedeagus as in Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2450283086BB6EAE36464821B95F320F" captionStart="Figure 9" captionStartId="F9" captionText="Figure 9. Male genitalia of subgenus Bembidion Hydrium A B. levigatum (voucher DNA 1693, Virginia: Danville City Co., Danville) B B. levigatum (voucher DNA 2343, Texas: Bastrop Co., Colorado River near Utley) C B. mimbres (voucher DNA 2134, USA: New Mexico: Grant Co., Gila River, Billings Vista) D B. mimbres (voucher DNA 2135, USA: New Mexico: Grant Co., Gila River, Billings Vista). Scale bar: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1007.60012.figure9" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/492373" pageId="0" pageNumber="85">9A, B</figureCitation>
. A very widespread species, found throughout most of the eastern United States and a small region of southern Canada, from Maine to Florida, north and west to Alberta and Montana, south to Utah, New Mexico, Texas, and Mexico (
<bibRefCitation id="7BC3E8C1603569322261A6B2D0E0D8DA" DOI="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.245.3416" author="Bousquet, Y" journalOrPublisher="ZooKeys" pageId="0" pageNumber="85" pagination="1 - 1722" refId="B2" refString="Bousquet, Y, 2012. Catalogue of Geadephaga (Coleoptera, Adephaga) of America, north of Mexico. ZooKeys 245: 1 - 1722, DOI: https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.245.3416" title="Catalogue of Geadephaga (Coleoptera, Adephaga) of America, north of Mexico." url="https://doi.org/10.3897/zookeys.245.3416" volume="245" year="2012">Bousquet 2012</bibRefCitation>
). I have also seen specimens from the Grand Canyon in northern Arizona (two specimens in MSBA labeled &quot;USA AZ Coconino Co Grand Canyon Nat. Park, N36.77 W111.655 RMBL 29-30 August 2002 coll. Cobb, Brantley, Lightfoot&quot;).
</paragraph>
